    {\displaystyle (\delta E)^{2}=\left\langle \psi |H^{2}|\psi \right\rangle -(\left\langle \psi |H|\psi \right\rangle )^{2}}
  is the variance of the system's energy and 
  
    
      
        H
      
    
    {\displaystyle H}
   is the Hamiltonian operator. 
The theorem is named after Leonid Mandelstam and Igor Tamm.
In this case, quantum evolution is independent of the particular Hamiltonian used to transport the quantum system along a given curve in the projective Hilbert space; it is the distance along this curve measured by the Fubini-Study metric.

